title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger 10/22 Takedown Rifle plus Simmons Protarget 3-9X40 Scope
postcontent:
I have a brand new Ruger 10/22 Takedown with a Simmons Protarget 3-9X40 scope mounted with Talley high rings. As soon as this rifle was released I knew I had to own one. I've had 10/22s with Butler Creek's Packer stock which allowed the easy removal of the barrel without tools so the gun could be easily carried in a backpack or small duffel and made for an excellent bug-out tool. But the problem with the Packer stock was that the barrel fit loosened over time and became inaccurate. Ruger fixed all that with this model and is now their most sought after (and nearly impossible to find) .10/22. Once I found one I immediately installed a new Simmons Protarget scope using Talley's rings that mount directly to the receiver so the Weaver rail that typically shoots loose after awhile is bypassed. This Simmons scope has target turrets, Truplex reticle and a ballistic dial calibrated for .22 long rifle rounds. Because this rifle has never been fired it will be up to the new owner to bore sight and zero the scope. All packing for both the firearm and scope are included. 

The following description is from Ruger:

Sturm, Ruger & Company, Inc. is proud to introduce the Ruger® 10/22 Takedown™. Readily separated into two subassemblies, the Ruger 10/22 Takedown offers a convenient transport and storage option for the popular Ruger® 10/22®. As reliable and accurate as every 10/22, the Ruger 10/22 Takedown makes it even easier to keep America's favorite rimfire rifle by your side. 

The barrel and forend of the Ruger 10/22 Takedown are easily separated from the action and buttstock by pushing a recessed lever, twisting the subassemblies, and pulling them apart. Reassembly is the reverse of takedown, and is quick and easy. The friction fit lockup of the assembly joint is simple to adjust, but will rarely need re-adjustment after the first assembly. The lockup is secure and repeatable, ensuring an accurate return to zero, even when receiver-mounted optics are used.

The Ruger 10/22 Takedown is shipped in a ballistic nylon backpack-style case that features internal sleeves which hold the subassemblies. External pockets with MOLLE webbing provide storage for magazines, ammunition, and other accessories. Multiple attachment points for the padded, single shoulder strap offer different carrying options.

The 4.67-pound Ruger 10/22 Takedown is 37" long when assembled; each subassembly is less than 20 1/4" long when disassembled. Utilizing the standard 10/22 action and ten round rotary magazine (one magazine is provided), the Ruger 10/22 Takedown offers legendary 10/22 reliability in a compact and portable package.

title: For Sale:  Re, The Bill
postcontent:
I don't know how you read it but if they pass this bill I will guarantee that Glocks/ARs/AKs and anything that accepts a mag that holds more than 10 rounds are in the list of 120 guns right at the beginning. Some peoples prices are ridiculous but go and look on gunbroker at auctions that have sold or selling, they are bringing these ridiculous prices because people think their's a chance they will not be able to purchase these firearms later. This is a free-market economy last time I checked so it is perfectly legal for people to raise prices based on demand and it will come back down once the supply catches up, if a bill does not passes right away. Am I going to pay these ridiculous prices? no, If you do not want to pay these inflated prices all you have to do is wait for the prices to come back down, if they do. 

Following is a summary of the 2013 legislation:

    Bans the sale, transfer, importation, or manufacturing of:
        120 specifically-named firearms
        Certain other semiautomatic rifles, handguns, shotguns that can accept a detachable magazine and have one military characteristic
        Semiautomatic rifles and handguns with a fixed magazine that can accept more than 10 rounds
    Strengthens the 1994 Assault Weapons Ban and various state bans by:
        Moving from a 2-characteristic test to a 1-characteristic test
        Eliminating the easy-to-remove bayonet mounts and flash suppressors from the characteristics test
        Banning firearms with “thumbhole stocks” and “bullet buttons” to address attempts to “work around” prior bans
    Bans large-capacity ammunition feeding devices capable of accepting more than 10 rounds.
    Protects legitimate hunters and the rights of existing gun owners by:
        Grandfathering weapons legally possessed on the date of enactment
        Exempting over 900 specifically-named weapons used for hunting or sporting purposes and
        Exempting antique, manually-operated, and permanently disabled weapons
    Requires that grandfathered weapons be registered under the National Firearms Act, to include:
        Background check of owner and any transferee;
        Type and serial number of the firearm;
        Positive identification, including photograph and fingerprint;
        Certification from local law enforcement of identity and that possession would not violate State or local law; and
        Dedicated funding for ATF to implement registration

I have a complete AR-15 lower I'm considering trading for an upper.

title: For Sale:  1916 "Peter The Great" Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
M91 1916 Peter The Great Mosin Nagant.

Tula Emperor Peter The Great Ordnance Factory.After trials of several different repeating bolt action designs Russia adopted a new standard infantry rifle in 1891. It fires the 7.62x54r cartridge and is a combination of designs by Russian Sergei Mosin and Belgian Leon Nagant whose primary contribution was the magazine and feed system. The official Russian designation is “Three Line Rifle, Model of the Year 1891” but is more commonly known in the US as the Mosin Nagant M91. A “line” is a unit of measure equal to 1/10th of an inch. Production of the M91 took place at the Russian arsenals at Izhevsk, Tula, and Sestroryetsk. Due to a slow start in domestic production a contract was issued to the French arms company Chatellerault who built around 500,000 M91s. During WWI contracts were issued to the American firms of New England Westinghouse and Remington for 1.8 and 1.5 million rifles respectively. M91s were widely used in WWI and can be found with markings from many different European countries that purchased or captured them.

This Rifle probably seen action in both World Wars.

title: For Sale:  Best of 500 Imported - CZ52 Pistol - Get Ready For The Ban
postcontent:
What I have is a CZ52 Czech pistol that was imported by CIA about 12 years ago. I paid a significant premium to get a hand pick of the best conditioned one of 500 lots brought in. 

The gun includes a second magazine, a cleaning rod, a military / police holster (authentic) and the shipping box. 

Sold pending funds
Also included is just shy of 100 rounds of the FMJ 7.62x25 FMJ ammunition for the gun. The ammo is readily available online and at Cabelas. 

There are several hodge-podge mismatched guns like this for sale on Arms List with no accessories or ammo, poor condition, for what I'm asking. No-nonsense price of $450 cash, well under what guns of this condition sell for on gunbroker.

What you need to know: The gun's cartridge shoots a necked case round that can build high pressure and operates on the same ballistic principles as the FN Five seveN. Military/Police agencies have access to bullets for this gun that circumvent class II kevlar body armor so the Brady Campaign has seen fit to target these types of guns/ammunition for special ban consideration. You obviously cannot buy such law enforcement only ammunition but it nonetheless makes the gun a very likely to be banned on the principle that such ammo exists somewhere in the world. 

Here's the quote from wikipedia, check out the wiki article for the sources:Due to its muzzle energy, higher pressure FMJ ammunition fired from the CZ 52 pistol will penetrate even NIJ II rated ballistic vests,[4] or the PASGT helmet.[5] 

The gun is Curio & Relic FFL 03 eligible. Illinois residents require a FOID card and valid State ID to purchase the handgun. No shenanigans, the sale will be lawful in every way. 

Trades considered: towards ARs, AKs, P90s, SCARS, MR556, MK23 SOCOM, Vintage Side by Side Shotguns. Or Premium 5.56x45 ammunition. Nothing else appeals to me.

 Dear,

 I am writing you regarding the numerous gun control schemes currently being proposed. I strongly oppose any additional gun control measures, including, but not limited to, those restricting magazines or so called "assault weapons". Guns are not the problem. If guns or access to guns were the problem, then Vermont, with some of the most lenient gun laws in the country, which doesn't even require a permit to carry concealed, would not consistently have some of the lowest homicide rates in the nation. Just 1.1 homicides / per 100,000 population in 2010, which was about 1/4 of the national average. So much for argument that availability of guns increases homicide rates.

For example in 2011, according to the FBI Uniform Crime Reports, rifles, including "assault" rifles were used in 2.55% of homicides. The UCR does not track how many of these specifically involved an "assault" rifle, however, it is obviously less than 2.55% for 2011 since that is the total for ALL rifles combined. By contrast personal weapons (hands, fists, feet, etc.) were used as the murder weapon in 5.75% of homicides in 2011 and knives and cutting instruments were used in 13.38% of homicides. Other years are similar.

 www.fbi.gov/about-us/cjis/ucr/crime-in-the-u.s/2011/crime-in-the-u.s.-2011/tables/expanded-homicide-data-table-8

Neither had any effect on the school shooter there, other than perhaps to guarantee his success by insuring that he was the only one armed. Compare the Sandy Hook tragedy, where nobody but the killer was armed, to the 1997 Pearl Mississippi school shooting where Vice Principal Joel Myrick was able to retrieve his handgun from his truck (it was illegal for him to possess or carry it in the school) and apprehend the shooter, Luke Woodham without Myrick firing a single shot. Luke Woodham's admitted plan after attacking his high school, was to go to the local Jr. High and continue his rampage there. Myrick stopped that plan cold. Unfortunately, there was no ARMED Joel Myrick at Sandy Hook. In another incident, in 2001, senior Jason Hoffman opened fire at Granite Hills High School in El Cajon, California. Hoffman wounded five people before being shot and incapacitated by, ARMED school resource officer (a police officer) Richard Agundez.



 We don't need more gun control, which has failed over and over every time it's been tried. We need real security, not useless 'feel good' measures that strip us of our constitutional rights for the mere illusion of safety. We need ARMED police officers in schools. These officers can provide security from all levels of threats as well as serve as badly needed role models for the children they protect. Giving the Joel Myricks of our country the ability to legally possess the guns they need to responsibly protect themselves and the children in their care wouldn't hurt either.

 Sincerely,
